summary: Thanks. At this rate this rate they should have just left them out of CM especially Monica.
question: Thanks. At this rate this rate they should have just left them out of CM especially Monica.
answer:
I’m personally not all that upset about it and was fine with their inclusion, but to each his own, I guess. I’m waiting to see if they include her in future movies given she’s an adult in present day.

And honestly, I doubt leaving them out would have made the situation better for the people who are upset. I’ve been on this site long enough to know that the complaint would’ve been that she was erased entirely from the narrative and that they chose the white female Captain Marvel over the black one who came first.

So yeah… short of having the movie just be about Monica as Captain Marvel, I really don’t think anything else would’ve made certain people happy. And that’s fine - people are entitled to their feelings. It’s just not how I feel.

summary: I really hope we see more of Nick’s characterization from Captain Marvel in Far From Home. More like how he was towards Tony in...
body:
I really hope we see more of Nick’s characterization from Captain Marvel in Far From Home. More like how he was towards Tony in Age of Ultron. Even if we’re excluding CM, Nick’s been shown to be very close to Nat, Tony, Maria (H), Phil, and even Steve post Winter Soldier. Like, he’s a good dude, and it’d be so cool to see him interacting with Peter in this same vein. 

(Also, I want at least one lowkey goofy scene with Nick in FFH. Maybe Nick turns on his phone, and it’s a pic of him, Goose, Carol, Maria, and Monica. And Peter like looks over his shoulder, and Peter’s like “Who are they?” And Nick just smiles and goes, “My Agents”.)

summary: why people don’t like strong female characters
title: why people don’t like strong female characters
body: i think i finally realized why lots of people(even girls) don’t like strong female characters. it’s because strong girls are immediately linked to feminists. they think that the only reason some character was made was for the “feminist movement”, which she isn’t! no one complains when a guy character is strong. no one thought when captain america’s movie was made that it was made because they want men to watch it. they know that the people who made it made it because they were all like “this guy is a cool character so they made a movie about him, it’s the only logical decision.” which, yes!! correct!! they like the character and want you to like him!! but when captain marvel was announced all these people went “this is just for feminists!! you’re only making this for the feminists you guys hate men this is going to be a trash movie!!” like,,,no. they didn’t make this movie or character for feminists. they made it so you would know more about the character and because she has cool powers. maybe feminists will enjoy it too, but that’s not why it was made at all. if captain marvel’s entire movie was exactly the same except she was a guy, everyone would’ve liked it and him. tl;dr: people think strong female characters are made for feminists when they’re just made because they’re cool characters. if captain marvel was exactly the same but with a guy there would be no issues.

body:
Me and The Avengers

I grew up essentially with the movies. Starting at Iron Man, to be frank. I was 5 and a half when the first one came out. And the stuff Tony could do, like a build a functioning, well armoured suit, just with a strong understanding of the fields necessary to make it(engineering, different sciences) sparked an interest in thode fields, made me curious at a young age about what I could do with an understanding about something within the world. And to this day, no one but me knew this fact. They just blamed it on me being a child.

When I sparked an interest in all the other movies as I got older, I got really curious about combat and different styles and martial arts. I began to want to be like Black Widow, Hawkeye, Captain America, etc. I hid this because I knew I’d be told that I shouldn’t learn how to fight “because i’m a girl”. I maintained having Iron Man and Black Widow as role models for myself.

When Captain Marvel came out, and I finally saw it April 23rd, she became one too. Why? Because I am 16 years old and she is a strong, independent woman who can easily take down her opponents. This strengthened during Endgame. And by the end, Captain Marvel and Iron Man became the main two people I wish to be like as I get older.

They are my role models and heroes, because they spark and continue interests within me that I will never lose.
